        <h2>XSS Prevention Tips</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Sanitize Input:</strong> Make sure that all user inputs are properly sanitized and validated to prevent malicious code from being injected.</li>
            <li><strong>Escape Output:</strong> Use encoding techniques for any data rendered on the webpage, especially within HTML, JavaScript, and CSS, to prevent scripts from executing.</li>
            <li><strong>Use Content Security Policy (CSP):</strong> Implement CSP headers to restrict the types of content that can be loaded and executed on your site, reducing the chances of executing malicious scripts.</li>
            <li><strong>Disable Inline JavaScript:</strong> Avoid using inline JavaScript code in your HTML files. Instead, use external scripts that are easier to control and audit.</li>
            <li><strong>Limit User Permissions:</strong> Restrict user roles and permissions on the server to limit the impact of potential attacks.</li>
            <li><strong>Use HTTP-Only Cookies:</strong> Set cookies to HTTP-Only and Secure to reduce the risk of cookie theft through XSS attacks.</li>
            <li><strong>Regular Security Audits:</strong> Conduct frequent security assessments to identify and fix any vulnerabilities in your application.</li>
        </ul>
